My brother was born in 1958.  When he was old enough to walk with us
(as opposed to being carried around), my mother put a harness and
leash on him.  She always knew where he was when we were out and
about, and she was always within range of effective discipline.  I
can't remember a single person ever criticizing her for leashing him.
When he was old enough to mind her, she took off the harness and
leash, and he heeled quite nicely.  (Sorry, couldnt' resist. &lt;Grin&gt;)

He's alive and well today, and (moderately) well adjusted.  I can't
see that being leashed hurt him the least little bit.  It didn't seem
to stifle his creativity any; he's a wood sculptor and furniture-
builder.

